# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cross-site-scripting-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The term "CSRF" is also used as an abbreviation in defences against CSRF attacks, such as techniques that use header data, form data, or cookies, to test for and prevent such attacks.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] In a CSRF attack, the attacker's goal is to cause an innocent victim to unknowingly submit a maliciously crafted web request to a website that the victim has privileged access to.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] This web request can be crafted to include URL parameters, cookies and other data that appear normal to the web server processing the request.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] At risk are web applications that perform actions based on input from trusted and authenticated users without requiring the user to authorize (e.g. via a popup confirmation) the specific action.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] A user who is authenticated by a cookie saved in the user's web browser could unknowingly send an HTTP request to a site that trusts the user and thereby cause an unwanted action.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] A general property of web browsers is that they will automatically and invisibly include any cookies (including session cookies and others) used by a given domain in any web request sent to that domain.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] This property is exploited by CSRF attacks.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] In order for a CSRF attack to work, an attacker must identify a reproducible web request that executes a specific action such as changing an account password on the target page.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Once such a request is identified, a link can be created that generates this malicious request and that link can be embedded on a page within the attacker's control.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] This link may be placed in such a way that it is not even necessary for the victim to click the link.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] For example, it may be embedded within an html image tag on an email sent to the victim which will automatically be loaded when the victim opens their email.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Once the victim has clicked the link, their browser will automatically include any cookies used by that website and submit the request to the web server.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The web server will not be able to identify the forgery because the request was made by a user that was logged in, and submitted all the requisite cookies.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Cross-site request forgery is an example of a confused deputy attack against a web browser because the web browser is tricked into submitting a forged request by a less privileged attacker.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] CSRF Token vulnerabilities have been known and in some cases exploited since 2001.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Because it is carried out from the user's IP address, some website logs might not have evidence of CSRF.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Attackers who can find a reproducible link that executes a specific action on the target page while the victim is logged in can embed such link on a page they control and trick the victim into opening it.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The attack carrier link may be placed in a location that the victim is likely to visit while logged into the target site (for example, a discussion forum), or sent in an HTML email body or attachment.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Attacks were launched by placing malicious, automatic-action HTML image elements on forums and email spam, so that browsers visiting these pages would open them automatically, without much user action.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] People running vulnerable μTorrent version at the same time as opening these pages were susceptible to the attack.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] When accessing the attack link to the local μTorrent application at localhost:8080, the browser would also always automatically send any existing cookies for that domain.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] This general property of web browsers enables CSRF attacks to exploit their targeted vulnerabilities and execute hostile actions as long as the user is logged into the target website (in this example, the local μTorrent web interface) at the time of the attack.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Because of this assumption, many existing CSRF prevention mechanisms in web frameworks will **not** cover GET requests, but rather apply the protection only to HTTP methods that are intended to be state-changing.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] An attacker may forge a request to log the victim into a target website using the attacker's credentials; this is known as *login CSRF*.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Login CSRF makes various novel attacks possible; for instance, an attacker can later log into the site with their legitimate credentials and view private information like activity history that has been saved in the account.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] This attack has been demonstrated against Google and Yahoo.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Depending on the type, the HTTP request methods vary in their susceptibility to the CSRF attacks (due to the differences in their handling by the web browsers).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Therefore, the protective measures against an attack depend on the method of the HTTP request.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] CSRF tokens could also be sent to a client by an attacker due to session fixation or other vulnerabilities, or guessed via a brute-force attack, rendered on a malicious page that generates thousands of failed requests.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The attack class of "Dynamic CSRF", or using a per-client payload for session-specific forgery, was described in 2009 by Nathan Hamiel and Shawn Moyer at the BlackHat Briefings, though the taxonomy has yet to gain wider adoption.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] A new vector for composing dynamic CSRF attacks was presented by Oren Ofer at a local OWASP chapter meeting in January 2012 – "AJAX Hammer – Dynamic CSRF".
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Severity metrics have been issued for CSRF token vulnerabilities that result in remote code execution with root privileges as well as a vulnerability that can compromise a root certificate, which will completely undermine a public key infrastructure.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The attacker must find a state-changing action at the target site, such as a form submission or a URL that does something (e.g., transfers money, or changes the victim's e-mail address or password).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Actions that only retrieve data are not useful as CSRF targets, because the attacker does not receive the response.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The attacker must determine the right values for all the forms or URL inputs; if any of them are required to be secret authentication values or IDs that the attacker can't guess, the attack will fail.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The attacker must lure the victim to a web page with malicious code while the victim is logged into the target site.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The victim has to be authenticated in a way that is automatically included in browser requests, such as a session cookie.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] This enables authentication to be included in the attacker's malicious requests.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The attack is blind: the attacker cannot see what the target website sends back to the victim in response to the forged requests, unless they exploit a cross-site scripting vulnerability or other bug at the target website.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Similarly, the attacker can only target any links or submit any forms that come up after the initial forged request if those subsequent links or forms are similarly predictable.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Multiple targets can be simulated by including multiple images on a page, or by using JavaScript to introduce a delay between clicks.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Most CSRF prevention techniques work by embedding additional authentication data into requests that allows the web application to detect requests from unauthorized locations.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Synchronizer token pattern (STP) is a technique where a token, a secret and unique value for each request, is embedded by the web application in all HTML forms and verified on the server side.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The token may be generated by any method that ensures unpredictability and uniqueness (e.g. using a hash chain of random seed).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] This is called an anti-forgery token in ASP.NET.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The attacker is thus unable to place a correct token in their requests to authenticate them.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] STP is the most compatible as it only relies on HTML, but introduces some complexity on the server side, due to the burden associated with checking validity of the token on each request.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] As the token is unique and unpredictable, it also enforces proper sequence of events (e.g. screen 1, then 2, then 3) which raises usability problem (e.g. user opens multiple tabs).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] It can be relaxed by using per session CSRF token instead of per request CSRF token.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Security of this technique is based on the assumption that only JavaScript running on the client side of an HTTPS connection to the server that initially set the cookie will be able to read the cookie's value.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] JavaScript running from a rogue file or email should not be able to successfully read the cookie value to copy into the custom header.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Even though the csrf-token **cookie** may be automatically sent with the rogue request, subject to the cookies SameSite policy, the server will still expect a valid X-Csrf-Token **header**.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The CSRF token itself should be unique and unpredictable.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The CSRF token cookie must not have httpOnly flag, as it is intended to be read by JavaScript by design.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] This technique is implemented by many modern frameworks, such as Django and AngularJS.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Because the token remains constant over the whole user session, it works well with AJAX applications, but does not enforce sequence of events in the web application.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Similarly to the cookie-to-header approach, but without involving JavaScript, a site can set a CSRF token as a cookie, and also insert it as a hidden field in each HTML form.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] When the form is submitted, the site can check that the cookie token matches the form token.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The same-origin policy prevents an attacker from reading or setting cookies on the target domain, so they cannot put a valid token in their crafted form.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The advantage of this technique over the Synchronizer pattern is that the token does not need to be stored on the server.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] However, if the site in question has cookie setting functionality, this protection can be bypassed.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] An additional "SameSite" attribute can be included when the server sets a cookie, instructing the browser on whether to attach the cookie to cross-site requests.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] If this attribute is set to "strict", then the cookie will only be sent on same-site requests, making CSRF ineffective.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] However, this requires the browser to recognise and correctly implement the attribute.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Browser extensions such as RequestPolicy (for Mozilla Firefox) or uMatrix (for both Firefox and Google Chrome/Chromium) can prevent CSRF by providing a default-deny policy for cross-site requests.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] However, this can significantly interfere with the normal operation of many websites.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The CsFire extension (also for Firefox) can mitigate the impact of CSRF with less impact on normal browsing, by removing authentication information from cross-site requests.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The NoScript extension for Firefox mitigates CSRF threats by distinguishing trusted from untrusted sites, and removing authentication & payloads from POST requests sent by untrusted sites to trusted ones.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The Application Boundary Enforcer module in NoScript also blocks requests sent from internet pages to local sites (e.g. localhost), preventing CSRF attacks on local services (such as uTorrent) or routers.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] The Self Destructing Cookies extension for Firefox does not directly protect from CSRF, but can reduce the attack window, by deleting cookies as soon as they are no longer associated with an open tab.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-request-forgery] Cross-site scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities (even in other applications running on the same domain) allow attackers to bypass essentially all CSRF preventions.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] OWASP considers the term cross-site scripting to be a misnomer.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] It initially was an attack that was used for breaching data across sites, but gradually started to include other forms of data injection attacks.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Security on the web depends on a variety of mechanisms, including an underlying concept of trust known as the same-origin policy.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Content from URLs where any of these three attributes are different will have to be granted permissions separately.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks use known vulnerabilities in web-based applications, their servers, or the plug-in systems on which they rely.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Exploiting one of these, attackers fold malicious content into the content being delivered from the compromised site.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] When the resulting combined content arrives at the client-side web browser, it has all been delivered from the trusted source, and thus operates under the permissions granted to that system.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] By finding ways of injecting malicious scripts into web pages, an attacker can gain elevated access-privileges to sensitive page content, to session cookies, and to a variety of other information maintained by the browser on behalf of the user.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks are a case of code injection.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Microsoft security-engineers introduced the term "cross-site scripting" in January 2000.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] The definition gradually expanded to encompass other modes of code injection, including persistent and non-JavaScript vectors (including ActiveX, Java, VBScript, Flash, or even HTML scripts), causing some confusion to newcomers to the field of information security.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities have been reported and exploited since the 1990s.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Prominent sites affected in the past include the social-networking sites Twitter and Facebook.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting flaws have since surpassed buffer overflows to become the most common publicly reported security vulnerability, with some researchers in 2007 estimating as many as 68% of websites are likely open to XSS attacks.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] There is no single, standardized classification of cross-site scripting flaws, but most experts distinguish between at least two primary flavors of XSS flaws: *non-persistent* and *persistent*.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Some sources further divide these two groups into *traditional* (caused by server-side code flaws) and *DOM-based* (in client-side code).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] The *non-persistent* (or *reflected*) cross-site scripting vulnerability is by far the most basic type of web vulnerability.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] These holes show up when the data provided by a web client, most commonly in HTTP query parameters (e.g.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] HTML form submission), is used immediately by server-side scripts to parse and display a page of results for that user, without properly sanitizing the content.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Because HTML documents have a flat, serial structure that mixes control statements, formatting, and the actual content, any non-validated user-supplied data included in the resulting page without proper HTML encoding, may lead to markup injection.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of a potential vector is a site search engine: if one searches for a string, the search string will typically be redisplayed verbatim on the result page to indicate what was searched for.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] If this response does not properly escape or reject HTML control characters, a cross-site scripting flaw will ensue.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] A reflected attack is typically delivered via email or a neutral web site.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] The bait is an innocent-looking URL, pointing to a trusted site but containing the XSS vector.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] If the trusted site is vulnerable to the vector, clicking the link can cause the victim's browser to execute the injected script.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of this is with online message boards where users are allowed to post HTML formatted messages for other users to read.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] For example, suppose there is a dating website where members scan the profiles of other members to see if they look interesting.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] For privacy reasons, this site hides everybody's real name and email.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] The only time a member's real name and email are in the browser is when the member is signed in, and they can't see anyone else's.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Suppose that Mallory, an attacker, joins the site and wants to figure out the real names of the people she sees on the site.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] To do so, she writes a script designed to run from other users' browsers when *they* visit *her* profile.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] The script then sends a quick message to her own server, which collects this information.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] To do this, for the question "Describe your Ideal First Date", Mallory gives a short answer (to appear normal), but the text at the end of her answer is her script to steal names and emails.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] If the script is enclosed inside a `<script>` element, it won't be shown on the screen.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Then suppose that Bob, a member of the dating site, reaches Mallory's profile, which has her answer to the First Date question.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Her script is run automatically by the browser and steals a copy of Bob's real name and email directly from his own machine.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Persistent XSS vulnerabilities can be more significant than other types because an attacker's malicious script is rendered automatically, without the need to individually target victims or lure them to a third-party website.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Particularly in the case of social networking sites, the code would be further designed to self-propagate across accounts, creating a type of client-side worm.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] The methods of injection can vary a great deal; in some cases, the attacker may not even need to directly interact with the web functionality itself to exploit such a hole.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Any data received by the web application (via email, system logs, IM etc.) that can be controlled by an attacker could become an injection vector.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities were originally found in applications that performed all data processing on the server side.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] User input (including an XSS vector) would be sent to the server, and then sent back to the user as a web page.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] The need for an improved user experience resulted in popularity of applications that had a majority of the presentation logic (maybe written in JavaScript) working on the client-side that pulled data, on-demand, from the server using AJAX.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] As the JavaScript code was also processing user input and rendering it in the web page content, a new sub-class of reflected XSS attacks started to appear that was called *DOM-based cross-site scripting*.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] In a DOM-based XSS attack, the malicious data does not touch the web server.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Rather, it is being reflected by the JavaScript code, fully on the client side.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] An example of a DOM-based XSS vulnerability is the bug found in 2011 in a number of jQuery plugins.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Prevention strategies for DOM-based XSS attacks include very similar measures to traditional XSS prevention strategies but implemented in JavaScript code and contained in web pages (i.e. input validation and escaping).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Some JavaScript frameworks have built-in countermeasures against this and other types of attack — for example AngularJS.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Self-XSS is a form of XSS vulnerability that relies on social engineering in order to trick the victim into executing malicious JavaScript code in their browser.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Although it is technically not a true XSS vulnerability due to the fact it relies on socially engineering a user into executing code rather than a flaw in the affected website allowing an attacker to do so, it still poses the same risks as a regular XSS vulnerability if properly executed.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Mutated XSS happens when the attacker injects something that is seemingly safe but is rewritten and modified by the browser while parsing the markup.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] This makes it extremely hard to detect or sanitize within the website's application logic.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] An example is rebalancing unclosed quotation marks or even adding quotation marks to unquoted values in CSS font-family properties.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] There are several escaping schemes that can be used depending on where the untrusted string needs to be placed within an HTML document including HTML entity encoding, JavaScript escaping, CSS escaping, and URL (or percent) encoding.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Most web applications that do not need to accept rich data can use escaping to largely eliminate the risk of XSS attacks in a fairly straightforward manner.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Performing HTML entity encoding only on the five XML significant characters is not always sufficient to prevent many forms of XSS attacks, security encoding libraries are usually easier to use.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Some web template systems understand the structure of the HTML they produce and automatically pick an appropriate encoder.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Many operators of particular web applications (e.g. forums and webmail) allow users to utilize HTML markup.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] When accepting HTML input from users (say, `<b>very</b> large`), output encoding (such as `&lt;b&gt;very&lt;/b&gt; large`) will not suffice since the user input needs to be rendered as HTML by the browser (so it shows as `**very** large`, instead of `<b>very</b> large`).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Stopping an XSS attack when accepting HTML input from users is much more complex in this situation.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Often, untrusted HTML input must be run through an HTML sanitization engine to ensure that it does not contain potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Many validations rely on parsing out (blacklisting) specific "at risk" HTML tags such as the `<iframe>`, `<link>`, and `<script>` tag, or by only allowing certain tags and removing or escaping others.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Another popular method is to strip user input of " and ' however this can also be bypassed as the payload can be concealed with obfuscation.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Besides content filtering, other imperfect methods for cross-site scripting mitigation are also commonly used.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] One example is the use of additional security controls when handling cookie-based user authentication.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Many web applications rely on session cookies for authentication between individual HTTP requests, and because client-side scripts generally have access to these cookies, simple XSS exploits can steal these cookies.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] To mitigate this particular threat (though not the XSS problem in general), many web applications tie session cookies to the IP address of the user who originally logged in, then only permit that IP to use that cookie.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] This is effective in most situations (if an attacker is only after the cookie), but obviously breaks down in situations where an attacker is behind the same NATed IP address or web proxy as the victim, or the victim is changing his or her mobile IP.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Another mitigation present in Internet Explorer (since version 6), Firefox (since version 2.0.0.5), Safari (since version 4), Opera (since version 9.5) and Google Chrome, is an *HttpOnly* flag which allows a web server to set a cookie that is unavailable to client-side scripts.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] While beneficial, the feature can neither fully prevent cookie theft nor prevent attacks within the browser.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] While Web 2.0 and Ajax developers require the use of JavaScript, some web applications are written to allow operation without the need for any client-side scripts.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] This allows users, if they choose, to disable scripting in their browsers before using the application.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] In this way, even potentially malicious client-side scripts could be inserted unescaped on a page, and users would not be susceptible to XSS attacks.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Some browsers or browser plugins can be configured to disable client-side scripts on a per-domain basis.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] This approach is of limited value if scripting is allowed by default, since it blocks bad sites only *after* the user knows that they are bad, which is too late.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Functionality that blocks all scripting and external inclusions by default and then allows the user to enable it on a per-domain basis is more effective.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] This has been possible for a long time in Internet Explorer (since version 4) by setting up its so called "Security Zones", and in Opera (since version 9) using its "Site Specific Preferences".
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] A solution for Firefox and other Gecko-based browsers is the open source NoScript add-on which, in addition to the ability to enable scripts on a per-domain basis, provides some XSS protection even when scripts are enabled.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Another problem with script blocking is that many users do not understand it, and do not know how to properly secure their browsers.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Yet another drawback is that many sites do not work without client-side scripting, forcing users to disable protection for that site and opening their systems to vulnerabilities.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] The Firefox NoScript extension enables users to allow scripts selectively from a given page while disallowing others on the same page.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] For example, scripts from example.com could be allowed, while scripts from advertisingagency.com that are attempting to run on the same page could be disallowed.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types changes Web APIs to check that values have been trademarked as trusted.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] As long as programs only trademark trustworthy values, an attacker who controls a JavaScript string value cannot cause XSS.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types are designed to be auditable by blue teams.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] Another defense approach is to use automated tools that will remove XSS malicious code in web pages, these tools use static analysis and/or pattern matching methods to identify malicious codes potentially and secure them using methods like escaping.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] When a cookie is set with the `SameSite=Strict` parameter, it is stripped from all cross-origin requests.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] When set with `SameSite=Lax`, it is stripped from all non-"safe" cross-origin requests (that is, requests other than GET, OPTIONS, and TRACE which have read-only semantics).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/cross-site-scripting] The feature is implemented in Google Chrome since version 63 and Firefox since version 60.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] Users frequently input sensitive data on websites, such as names, addresses, passwords, and banking details.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] As a web developer, it's crucial to protect this information from bad actors who use a wide range of exploits to steal such information and use it for personal gain.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] The focus of web security is to help you protect your website against these exploits and secure your users' sensitive data.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] This page lists guides that summarize some best practices for implementing security features on websites.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] While these guides do not cover all possible security scenarios and cannot guarantee complete security of your website, following the information and best practices in these guides will make your sites significantly more secure.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] The guides in this section summarize best practices for implementing HTTP headers correctly to mitigate security issues, and are directly related to the HTTP Observatory tool.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] Observatory performs security audits on a website and provides a grade and score along with recommendations for fixing the security issues it finds.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] These guides explain how to resolve issues surfaced by the HTTP Observatory tests: the tool links to the relevant guide for each issue, helping guide you towards an effective resolution.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] Interestingly, Mozilla's internal developer teams use this guidance when implementing websites to ensure that security best practices are applied.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] The guides in the table below are listed in the order that we recommend implementing the security features they describe.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] This order is based on a combination of each feature's security impact and the ease of its implementation from both operational and developmental perspectives.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] The table provides information about each feature's impact, difficulty of implementation, whether or not it is required, and a brief description.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] Form fields support autocompletion; that is, their values can be remembered and automatically filled out next time a user visits your site.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/practical-implementation-guides] For certain types of data, you may wish to disable this feature; this article explains how.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] In computer science, **session hijacking**, sometimes also known as **cookie hijacking**, is the exploitation of a valid computer session—sometimes also called a *session key*—to gain unauthorized access to information or services in a computer system.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] In particular, it is used to refer to the theft of a magic cookie used to authenticate a user to a remote server.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] It has particular relevance to web developers, as the HTTP cookies used to maintain a session on many websites can be easily stolen by an attacker using an intermediary computer or with access to the saved cookies on the victim's computer (see HTTP cookie theft).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] After successfully stealing appropriate session cookies an adversary might use the Pass the Cookie technique to perform session hijacking.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Cookie hijacking is commonly used against client authentication on the internet.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Modern web browsers use cookie protection mechanisms to protect the web from being attacked.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] A popular method is using source-routed IP packets.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] This allows an attacker at point *B* on the network to participate in a conversation between *A* and *C* by encouraging the IP packets to pass through *B's* machine.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] If source-routing is turned off, the attacker can use "blind" hijacking, whereby it guesses the responses of the two machines.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Thus, the attacker can send a command, but can never see the response.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] However, a common command would be to set a password allowing access from elsewhere on the net.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] An attacker can also be "inline" between *A* and *C* using a sniffing program to watch the conversation.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] This is known as a "man-in-the-middle attack".
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] HTTP protocol versions 0.8 and 0.9 lacked cookies and other features necessary for session hijacking.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Version 0.9beta of Mosaic Netscape, released on October 13, 1994, supported cookies.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Early versions of HTTP 1.0 did have some security weaknesses relating to session hijacking, but they were difficult to exploit due to the vagaries of most early HTTP 1.0 servers and browsers.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] As HTTP 1.0 has been designated as a fallback for HTTP 1.1 since the early 2000s—and as HTTP 1.0 servers are all essentially HTTP 1.1 servers the session hijacking problem has evolved into a nearly permanent security risk.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] The introduction of supercookies and other features with the modernized HTTP 1.1 has allowed for the hijacking problem to become an ongoing security problem.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Webserver and browser state machine standardization has contributed to this ongoing security problem.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] There are four main methods used to perpetrate a session hijack.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] After successfully acquiring appropriate session cookies an adversary would inject the session cookie into their browser to impersonate the victim user on the website from which the session cookie was stolen from.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Attackers often rely on specialized tools to execute session hijacking attacks.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] One such tool is Firesheep, a Firefox extension introduced in October 2010.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Firesheep demonstrated session hijacking vulnerabilities in unsecured networks by capturing unencrypted cookies from popular websites, allowing users to take over active sessions of others on the same network.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] The tool worked by displaying potential targets in a sidebar, enabling session access without password theft.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Another widely used tool is Wireshark, a network protocol analyzer that allows attackers to monitor and intercept data packets on unsecured networks.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] If a website does not encrypt its session cookies or authentication tokens, attackers can extract them and use them to gain unauthorized access to a victim’s account.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Firesheep, a Firefox extension introduced in October 2010, demonstrated session hijacking vulnerabilities in unsecured networks.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] It captured unencrypted cookies from popular websites, allowing users to take over active sessions of others on the same network.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] The websites supported included Facebook, Twitter, Flickr, Amazon, Windows Live and Google, with the ability to use scripts to add other websites.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Only months later, Facebook and Twitter responded by offering (and later requiring) HTTP Secure throughout.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] DroidSheep is a simple Android tool for web session hijacking (sidejacking).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] It listens for HTTP packets sent via a wireless (802.11) network connection and extracts the session id from these packets in order to reuse them.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] DroidSheep can capture sessions using the libpcap library and supports: open (unencrypted) networks, WEP encrypted networks, and WPA/WPA2 encrypted networks (PSK only).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] This software uses libpcap and arpspoof.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] The apk was made available on Google Play but it has been taken down by Google.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] CookieCadger is a graphical Java app that automates sidejacking and replay of HTTP requests, to help identify information leakage from applications that use unencrypted GET requests.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] It is a cross-platform open-source utility based on the Wireshark suite which can monitor wired Ethernet, insecure Wi-Fi, or load a packet capture file for offline analysis.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Cookie Cadger has been used to highlight the weaknesses of youth team sharing sites such as Shutterfly (used by AYSO soccer league) and TeamSnap.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] CookieMonster is a man-in-the-middle exploit where a third party can gain HTTPS cookie data when the "Encrypted Sessions Only" property is not properly set.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] This could allow access to sites with sensitive personal or financial information.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] In 2008, this could affect major websites, including Gmail, Google Docs, eBay, Netflix, CapitalOne, Expedia.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] It is a Python based tool, developed by security researcher Mike Perry.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] Perry originally announced the vulnerability exploited by CookieMonster on BugTraq in 2007.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/session-hijacking] A year later, he demonstrated CookieMonster as a proof of concept tool at Defcon 16.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] In web security, an attack is a specific method an attacker uses to achieve their goal.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] For example, if their goal is to steal a user's data, a cross-site scripting (XSS) attack is one method they might use.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] A given attack may be countered by one or more mitigations: for example, XSS might be countered by properly sanitizing data and implementing a content security policy.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] This page links to pages explaining how some common attacks work, and how they can be mitigated.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] In a clickjacking attack, an attacker creates a decoy site which embeds the target site inside an `<iframe>` element.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] It hides the `<iframe>`, and overlays some decoy elements on top of it.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] When the user interacts with these decoy elements, they are inadvertently interacting with the target site, and may be tricked into performing actions with the target site which they did not intend.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] In a cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attack, an attacker tricks the user or the browser into making an HTTP request to the target site from a malicious site.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] The request includes the user's credentials and causes the server to carry out some harmful action, thinking that the user intended it.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] Cross-site leaks (XS-Leaks) are a class of attack in which an attacker's site can derive information about the target site, or about the user's relationship with the target site, by using web platform APIs that enable sites to interact with one another.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] In a cross-site scripting (XSS) attack, a website accepts some input crafted by the attacker and mistakenly includes this input in the site's own pages in a way that makes the browser execute it as code.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] The malicious code can then do anything that the site's own front-end code could do.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] In an Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR) attack, the attacker takes advantage of insufficient access control and insecure exposure of object identifiers, such as database keys or file paths.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] In a Manipulator in the Middle (MITM) attack, the attacker inserts themselves between the user's browser and the server, and can see and potentially modify any of the traffic exchanged over HTTP.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] Phishing is a social engineering attack in which the attacker steals a user's credentials by tricking them into believing they are signing into the target site, when in reality they are interacting with a fake site controlled by the attacker.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] JavaScript prototype pollution is a vulnerability where an attacker can add or modify properties on an object's prototype.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] This means malicious values can unexpectedly appear on objects in your application, often leading to logic errors or additional attacks like cross-site scripting (XSS).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] Server‑Side Request Forgery (SSRF) is a vulnerability that allows an attacker to make HTTP (or other network) requests to arbitrary destinations.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] SSRF makes these requests originate from within a server itself, which typically has broader access than an external client.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] In a subdomain takeover attack, the attacker gains control over a subdomain of a target domain.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/types-of-attacks] In a supply chain attack, the attacker compromises part of the site's supply chain, such as any third-party dependencies that it uses.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/x-content-type-options] The HTTP **`X-Content-Type-Options`** response header indicates that the MIME types advertised in the `Content-Type` headers should be respected and not changed.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/x-content-type-options] The header allows you to avoid MIME type sniffing by specifying that the MIME types are deliberately configured.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/x-content-type-options] Site security testers usually expect this header to be set (and that the `Content-Type` header is correctly set for all resources).
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/x-content-type-options] Blocks a request if the request destination is of type `style` and the MIME type is not `text/css`, or of type `script` and the MIME type is not a JavaScript MIME type.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/x-content-type-options] It also prevents MIME type sniffing for all other response types, causing the browser to use the declared `Content-Type` without examining the response content.
[src:cross-site-scripting-defense/x-content-type-options] In particular it prevents a browser from treating a response as `text/html` when it is loaded in a browsing context and the `Content-Type` header is absent or indicates a non-HTML type.
